                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      SAIL profit drops on lower sales
          OUR BUREAU                                            
	New Delhi, July 29: Steel Authority of India Ltds net profit for the first quarter of this fiscal dipped 11.55 per cent to Rs 1,176.55 crore from Rs 1,330.43 crore in the year-ago period on lower sales and high input cost.         
	The steel maker saw sales in terms of volume shrinking 0.46 million tonnes to 2.32 million tonnes. Input costs rose 40-45 per cent compared with the year-ago period.         
	Net sales for the quarter stood at Rs 9,133.32 crore compared with Rs 9,163.41 crore in the same period last fiscal.         
	Greater availability of steel worldwide coupled with pressure on demand made the market conditions quite testing for steel companies in the first quarter, SAIL chairman C.S. Verma said.        
	ONGC profit dips        
	State-run Oil amp; Natural Gas Corporation (ONGC) saw a 24.5 per cent decline in net profit at Rs 3,661.14 crore for the first quarter ended June against Rs 4,847.92 crore in the same period last year on higher subsidy payouts.         
	ONGC paid Rs 5,515 crore in the April-June quarter towards fuel subsidies against Rs 429 crore in the year-ago period, chairman and managing director R.S. Sharma said.        
	Honda net skids        
	Hero Honda today reported a 1.68 per cent decline in its profit after tax for the quarter ended June 30 at Rs 491.69 crore against Rs 500.11 crore in the same period last year on the back of rising commodity prices and switching over to new emission norms.        
	During the quarter, the company sold 12,34,039 units of two-wheelers, up 10 per cent.        
	Tata Beverages         
	Tata Global Beverages, formerly known as Tata Tea, has reported a consolidated net profit of Rs 45.56 crore for the quarter ended June 30 against a loss of Rs 19.57 crore in the year-ago period.         
	Net sales rose to Rs 1,373.89 crore, registering an 8 per cent growth, from Rs 1,275.11 crore in the year-ago period.        
	The company said growth in net sales was because of the higher price realisation.                                                                                                                                                   
